Filiation of Text

**FILIATION 3**The present text is a translation, and occasionally an expansion, of selected extracts from the much longer Latin original. No other Gaelic text related to this translation is currently known.

8. DE ORACIONE

1.
oir adeir an tigerna isa tsoisgel
a. gibeni 9. tirfighe orm maille hurnaighe agus bur credim co maith le do 10. ghebthaihe

Matt. 21:22

Lib. Scint VII:1: Omnia quecumque petieritis in orationem credentes, accipietis.

Agus ge b'e air bith nithean a dh'iarras sibh ann bhur n-urnuigh, ma chreideas sibh, gheibh sibh iad.


b. mased denaidh faire an gach uile aimser fa comair bur 11. inbedh dingbala do thechedh roim nert an gilla nach coir agus d anmain : a 12. d tsesam a fiagnuise mic righ nimhe agus talman

Luke 21:36

Lib. Scint VII:2: Vigilate itaque omni tempore orantes ut, regnum Dei digni, habeamini fugire omnia que futura sunt et stare ante Filium hominis.

Denaibhse air an aobhar sin faire, a' deanamh urnuigh gach àm, chum gu measar gur àiridh sibh air dol a o na nithibh sin uile a tha gu teachd, agus seasamh an làthair Mhic an duine.


c. agus denaidh urnaighe fa com 13. air gan tethedh an geimrigh no an tsamraid 1 do beidhoraib

Matt. 24:20

Lib. Scint VII:3: Orate autem ut non fiat fuga uestra hierne uel sabato.

Ach guidhibh-sa gun bhur teicheadh a bhi 's a' gheamradh, no air an t-sàbaid.

2.
oir adeir iac 14. op apstol
a. cuiridh bur nguidhe le cele agus slaneochur sib oir is mor 15. fhoghi{r}guidhe an firenda do shir

James 5:16

Lib. Scint VII:6: Orate in inuicem, ut saluimini. Multum enim ualit deprecatio iusti assidua.

Aidichibh bhur lochdan d'a chéile, agus deanaibh urnuigh air son a chéile, chum gu'n tearnar sibh: tha mòr éifeachd ann an urnuigh dhùrachdaich n fhìrein.

3.
oir adeir salimon
a. is fada in tigerna 16. o ghuide nan daine mitrocaireacaagus esdidh se guidhe na fir 17. enach

Prov. 15:29

Lib. Scint VII:7: Longe est Dominus ab impiis, et orationis iustorum exaudiet.

Tha-n Tighearn fada o na h-aingidh; ach éisdidh e ri h-urnuigh nam fìrean.


b. agus is fearr deredh na hurnaighe na tosach

Eccl. 7:9

Lib. Scint VII:8: Melior fines est orationis quam principium.

Is fearr deireadh ni na a thoiseach: is fearr esan a tha foghidneach 'n a spiorad na esan a tha àrdanach 'n a spiorad.


c. mased ullmhuidh 18. th anam roimh an urnaid agus na bi mur bis duine ag aimsiugud ar dia

Eccli. 18:23

Lib. Scint VII:9: Ante orationem praepara animam tuam, et noli esse quasi homo qui temptat Deum.

Dean deas, mu 'n dean thu ùrnuigh; agus na bi mar neach a bhrosnaicheas an Tighearna.


d. 19. oir gibecoimedus an dliged imdhaighe se na hurnaighe

Eccli. 35:1

Lib. Scint VII:10: Qui conseruat legem multiplicat orationem.

Bheir esan a ghléidheas an lagh ni 's leòir do thabhartasaibh; agus bheir esan tabhartas-sithe a bheir géill do 'n àithne.

4.
oir adeir isidurus
a. 20. gurob ann sa craide ata in urnaighe agus nach sa beil oir ni hiad bri 21. atra an ti ghuidhius do b[h]erada huigh ach a craidhe oir is ferr guidhe catai 22. maill[e] craidhe maith na guide maille briatraib arda gan meanm 23. ain leo oir da ndernair guidhe fholaigheach agad fen gin co follus do da 24. inib ni he[i]dir a b[h]eith folaigech ar dia agus is ann ghuidimaid co fir 25. inneach an tigerna an uair nach bi slighe ele ar ar naire cigh terc do ni 26. mar sin an guidhe et reliqua

Isidore of Seville, Sententiae III:7.4

Lib. Scint VII:27: Oratio cordis est non labiorum; neque enim uerba deprecantes Deus intendit, sed orantes cor aspicit. Melius est autem cum silentio orare cordis, quam solis uerbis sine intuitu mentis. Quod si tacite quis orat et vox sileat, quamuis hominibus lateat, Deo latere non potest, qui conscientie presens est.

Notes

1. At some point in the transmission, sabato ("sabbath") was misunderstood as samrad ("summer").

2. This is surely a mistake for "do chorp".

3. It is not clear whether the medieval translator is not taking "the king" as an alternative kenning for God.

4. This appears to refer to Peter, somehow.

5. The medieval translator seems to have misunderstood Abba as "son".

6. These words are actually spoken by John the Baptist.
